04927nam a22008295i 9781400865833DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2015    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008658337 a10.1515/97814008658332doi  a(DE-B1597)459917  a(OCoLC)904339000  a(OCoLC)984688370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aB802 7aHIS0370502bisacsh 7aPHI0160002bisacsh 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a190.9033223  aCF 12502rvk1 aFerrone, Vincenzo, eauthor.14aThe Enlightenment :bHistory of an Idea - Updated Edition /cVincenzo Ferrone.  aUpdated edition with a New afterword by the author 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Living the Enlightenment -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I. The Philosophers' Enlightenment -- t1. Historians and Philosophers -- t2. Kant: Was ist Aufklärung? -- t3. Hegel -- t4. Marx and Nietzsche -- t5. Horkheimer and Adorno -- t6. Foucault -- t7. Postmodern Anti-Enlightenment Positions -- tPart II. The Hitorians' Enlightenment -- t8. For a Defense of Historical Knowledge -- t9. The Epistemologia imaginabilis in Eighteenth-Century Science and Philosophy -- t10. The Enlightenment-French Revolution Paradigm -- t11. The Twentieth Century and the Enlightenment as Historical Problem -- t12. What Was the Enlightenment? -- t13. Chronology and Geography of a Cultural Revolution -- t14. Politicization and Natura naturans -- tAfterword The Enlightenment: A Revolution of the Mind or the Ancien Régime's Cultural Revolution? -- tNotes -- tIndex  aIn this concise and powerful book, one of the world's leading historians of the Enlightenment provides a bracing and clarifying new interpretation of this watershed period. Arguing that philosophical and historical interpretations of the era have long been hopelessly confused, Vincenzo Ferrone makes the case that it is only by separating these views and taking an approach grounded in social and cultural history that we can begin to grasp what the Enlightenment was-and why it is still relevant today. Ferrone explains why the Enlightenment was a profound and wide-ranging cultural revolution that reshaped Western identity, reformed politics through the invention of human rights, and redefined knowledge by creating a critical culture. These new ways of thinking gave birth to new values that spread throughout society and changed how everyday life was lived and understood. Featuring an illuminating afterword describing how his argument challenges the work of Anglophone interpreters including Jonathan Israel, The Enlightenment provides a fascinating reevaluation of the true nature and legacy of one of the most important and contested periods in Western history.The translation of this work has been funded by SEPS-Segretariato Europeo per le Pubblicazioni Scientifiche.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aEnlightenmentxHistoriography. 0aEnlightenment. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh1 aFerrone, Vincenzo.1 aTarantino, Elisabetta.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400865833zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400865833.jpg  a978-3-11-044418-6  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  a978-3-11-066592-5  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13E